  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. It is considered a serious financial crime that undermines the integrity of financial systems and facilitates other illegal activities such as corruption, fraud, and organized crime.\n\nIn China, money laundering is explicitly prohibited under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**, which was first enacted in 2007 and has since been updated to strengthen regulations. The law outlines legal responsibilities for financial institutions, businesses, and individuals to prevent, monitor, and report suspicious transactions. Violators can face severe penalties, including fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment, depending on the severity of the offense.\n\nChina actively cooperates with international efforts to combat money laundering through organizations such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** and has established robust mechanisms to detect, investigate, and prosecute money laundering activities. The Chinese government remains committed to maintaining a fair and transparent financial system while safeguarding national security and economic stability.",
